51 "§ 75F-3. Preemption; reference to other laws.
Page 6 DRS35438-LRa-166

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (a) This Chapter supersedes and preempts any ordinance, resolution, rule, or other
2 regulation adopted by a local political subdivision of the State regarding the processing of
3 personal data by a controller or processor.
4 (b) Any reference to federal law in this Chapter includes any rules or regulations
5 promulgated under the federal law.
6 "§ 75F-4. Consumer rights; access; deletion; portability; opt out of certain processing.
7 (a) A consumer has the right to:
8 (1) Confirm whether a controller is processing the consumer's personal data and
9 access the consumer's personal data.
10 (2) Delete the consumer's personal data that the consumer provided to the
11 controller.
12 (3) Obtain a copy of the consumer's personal data that the consumer previously
13 provided to the controller, in a format that to the extent technically feasible,
14 that is readily usable and allows the consumer to transmit the data to another
15 controller without impediment where the processing is carried out by
16 automated means.
17 (4) Opt out of the processing of the consumer's personal data for purposes of
18 targeted advertising or the sale of personal data.
19 (b) Nothing in this section requires a person to cause a breach of security system.
20 "§ 75F-5. Exercising consumer rights.
21 (a) A consumer may exercise a right by submitting a request to a controller, by means
22 prescribed by the controller, specifying the right the consumer intends to exercise.
23 (b) In the case of processing personal data concerning a known child, the parent or legal
24 guardian of the known child shall exercise a right on the child's behalf.
25 (c) In the case of processing personal data concerning a consumer subject to
26 guardianship, the guardian of the consumer shall exercise a right on the consumer's behalf.
27 "§ 75F-6. Controller's response to requests.
28 (a) Subject to the other provisions of this Chapter, a controller shall comply with a
29 consumer's request under G.S. 75F-5 to exercise a right.
30 (b) Within 45 days after the day on which a controller receives a request to exercise a
31 right, the controller shall take action on the consumer's request and inform the consumer of any
32 action taken on the consumer's request.
33 (c) The controller may extend once the initial 45-day period by an additional 45 days if
34 reasonably necessary due to the complexity of the request or the volume of the requests received
35 by the controller. If a controller extends the initial 45-day period, before the initial 45-day period
36 expires, the controller shall (i) inform the consumer of the extension, including the length of the
37 extension, and (ii) provide the reasons the extension is reasonably necessary.
38 (d) The 45-day period does not apply if the controller reasonably suspects the consumer's
39 request is fraudulent and the controller is not able to authenticate the request before the 45-day
40 period expires.
41 (e) If, in accordance with this section, a controller chooses not to take action on a
42 consumer's request, the controller shall within 45 days after the day on which the controller
43 receives the request inform the consumer of the reasons for not taking action.
44 (f) A controller may not charge a fee for information in response to a request, unless the
45 request is the consumer's second or subsequent request during the same 12-month period.
46 However, a controller may charge a reasonable fee to cover the administrative costs of complying
47 with a request or refuse to act on a request if:
48 (1) The request is excessive, repetitive, technically infeasible, or manifestly
49 unfounded;
50 (2) The controller reasonably believes the primary purpose in submitting the
51 request was something other than exercising a right; or
DRS35438-LRa-166 Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) The request, individually or as part of an organized effort, harasses, disrupts,
2 or imposes undue burden on the resources of the controller's business.
3 (g) A controller that charges a fee or refuses to act in accordance with this section bears
4 the burden of demonstrating the request satisfied one or more of the criteria described in this
5 section.
6 (h) If a controller is unable to authenticate a consumer request to exercise a right
7 described in G.S. 75F-4 using commercially reasonable efforts, the controller is not required to
8 comply with the request and may request that the consumer provide additional information
9 reasonably necessary to authenticate the request.
10 "§ 75F-7. Responsibilities according to role.
11 (a) A processor shall adhere to the controller's instructions, and taking into account the
12 nature of the processing and information available to the processor, by the appropriate technical
13 and organizational measures, insofar as reasonably practicable, assist the controller in meeting
14 the controller's obligations, including obligations related to the security of processing personal
15 data and notification of a breach of security system.
16 (b) Before a processor performs processing on behalf of a controller, the processor and
17 controller shall enter into a contract that does all of the following:
18 (1) Clearly sets forth instructions for processing personal data, the nature and
19 purpose of the processing, the type of data subject to processing, the duration
20 of the processing, and the parties' rights and obligations.
21 (2) Requires the processor to ensure each person processing personal data is
22 subject to a duty of confidentiality with respect to the personal data.
23 (3) Requires the processor to engage any subcontractor pursuant to a written
24 contract that requires the subcontractor to meet the same obligations as the
25 processor with respect to the personal data.
26 (c) Determining whether a person is acting as a controller or processor with respect to a
27 specific processing of data is a fact-based determination that depends upon the context in which
28 personal data are to be processed. A processor that adheres to a controller's instructions with
29 respect to a specific processing of personal data remains a processor.
30 "§ 75F-8. Responsibilities of contractors; transparency; purpose specification and data
31 minimization; consent for secondary use; security; nondiscrimination.
32 (a) A controller shall provide consumers with a reasonably accessible and clear privacy
33 notice that includes all of the following:
34 (1) The categories of personal data processed by the controller.
35 (2) The purposes for which the categories of personal data are processed.
36 (3) How consumers may exercise a right.
37 (4) The categories of personal data that the controller shares with third parties, if
38 any.
39 (5) The categories of third parties, if any, with whom the controller shares
40 personal data.
41 If a controller sells a consumer's personal data to one or more third parties or engages in targeted
42 advertising, the controller shall clearly and conspicuously disclose to the consumer the manner
43 in which the consumer may exercise the right to opt out of the sale of the consumer's personal
44 data or processing for targeted advertising.
45 (b) A controller shall establish, implement, and maintain reasonable administrative,
46 technical, and physical data security practices designed to protect the confidentiality and integrity
47 of personal data and reduce reasonably foreseeable risks of harm to consumers relating to the
48 processing of personal data. Considering the controller's business size, scope, and type, a
49 controller shall use data security practices that are appropriate for the volume and nature of the
50 personal data at issue.
