1 (c) Except as otherwise provided in this Chapter, a controller may not process sensitive
2 data collected from a consumer without first presenting the consumer with clear notice and an
3 opportunity to opt out of the processing or, in the case of the processing of personal data
4 concerning a known child, processing the data in accordance with the federal Children's Online
5 Privacy Protection Act, 15 U.S.C. § 6501 et seq., and the act's implementing regulations and
6 exemptions.
7 (d) A controller may not discriminate against a consumer for exercising a right by (i)
8 denying a good or service to the consumer, (ii) charging the consumer a different price or rate
9 for a good or service, or (iii) providing the consumer a different level of quality of a good or
10 service. Nothing in this subsection prohibits a controller from offering a different price, rate,
11 level, quality, or selection of a good or service to a consumer, including offering a good or service
12 for no fee or at a discount, if the consumer has opted out of targeted advertising or the offer is
13 related to the consumer's voluntary participation in a bona fide loyalty, rewards, premium
14 features, discounts, or club card program.
15 (e) A controller is not required to provide a product, service, or functionality to a
16 consumer if the consumer's personal data are, or the processing of the consumer's personal data
17 is, reasonably necessary for the controller to provide the consumer the product, service, or
18 functionality and the consumer does not provide the consumer's personal data to the controller
19 or allow the controller to process the consumer's personal data. Any provision of a contract that
20 purports to waive or limit a consumer's right under this Chapter is void.
21 "§ 75F-9. Processing de-identified data or pseudonymous data.
22 (a) The provisions of this Chapter do not require a controller or processor to do any of
23 the following:
24 (1) Reidentify de-identified data or pseudonymous data.
25 (2) Maintain data in identifiable form or obtain, retain, or access any data or
26 technology for the purpose of allowing the controller or processor to associate
27 a consumer request with personal data.
28 (3) Comply with an authenticated consumer request to exercise a right described
29 in G.S. 75F-4, if the controller:
30 a. Is not reasonably capable of associating the request with the personal
31 data or it would be unreasonably burdensome for the controller to
32 associate the request with the personal data;
33 b. Does not (i) use the personal data to recognize or respond to the
34 consumer who is the subject of the personal data or (ii) associate the
35 personal data with other personal data about the consumer; and
36 c. Does not sell or other otherwise disclose the personal data to any third
37 party other than a processor, except as otherwise permitted in this
38 section.
39 (b) The rights described in G.S. 75F-4(a)(1) through (a)(3) do not apply to pseudonymous
40 data if a controller demonstrates that any information necessary to identify a consumer is kept
41 separately and subject to appropriate technical and organizational measures to ensure the
42 personal data are not attributed to an identified individual or an identifiable individual.
43 (c) A controller who uses pseudonymous data or de-identified data shall take reasonable
44 steps to ensure the controller complies with any contractual obligations to which the
45 pseudonymous data or de-identified data are subject and promptly addresses any breach of a
46 contractual obligation.
47 "§ 75F-10. Limitations.
48 (a) The requirements described in this Chapter do not restrict a controller's or processor's
49 ability to do any of the following:
50 (1) Comply with a State, federal, or local law, rule, or regulation.
