1 (2) Comply with a civil, criminal, or regulatory inquiry, investigation, subpoena,
2 or summons by a federal, State, local, or other governmental entity.
3 (3) Cooperate with a law enforcement agency concerning activity that the
4 controller or processor reasonably and in good faith believes may violate
5 federal, State, or local laws, rules, or regulations.
6 (4) Investigate, establish, exercise, prepare for, or defend a legal claim.
7 (5) Provide a product or service requested by a consumer or a parent or legal
8 guardian of a child.
9 (6) Perform a contract to which the consumer or the parent or legal guardian of a
10 child is a party, including fulfilling the terms of a written warranty or taking
11 steps at the request of the consumer or parent or legal guardian before entering
12 into the contract with the consumer.
13 (7) Take immediate steps to protect an interest that is essential for the life or
14 physical safety of the consumer or of another individual.
15 (8) Detect, prevent, protect against, or respond to a security incident, identity
16 theft, fraud, harassment, malicious or deceptive activity, or any illegal activity
17 or investigate, report, or prosecute a person responsible for an action described
18 in this subdivision.
19 (9) Preserve the integrity or security of systems or investigate, report, or prosecute
20 a person responsible for harming or threatening the integrity or security of
21 systems.
22 (10) If the controller discloses the processing in a notice described in G.S. 75F-8,
23 engage in public or peer-reviewed scientific, historical, or statistical research
24 in the public interest that adheres to all other applicable ethics and privacy
25 laws.
26 (11) Assist another person with an obligation described in this subsection.
27 (12) Process personal data to do any of the following:
28 a. Conduct internal analytics or other research to develop, improve, or
29 repair a controller's or processor's product, service, or technology.
30 b. Identify and repair technical errors that impair existing or intended
31 functionality.
32 c. Effectuate a product recall.
33 (13) Process personal data to perform an internal operation that is (i) reasonably
34 aligned with the consumer's expectations based on the consumer's existing
35 relationship with the controller or (ii) otherwise compatible with processing
36 to aid the controller or processor in providing a product or service specifically
37 requested by a consumer or a parent or legal guardian of a child or the
38 performance of a contract to which the consumer or a parent or legal guardian
39 of a child is a party.
40 (14) Retain a consumer's email address to comply with the consumer's request to
41 exercise a right.
42 (b) This Chapter does not apply if a controller's or processor's compliance with this
43 Chapter:
44 (1) Violates an evidentiary privilege under North Carolina law.
45 (2) As part of a privileged communication, prevents a controller or processor from
46 providing personal data concerning a consumer to a person covered by an
47 evidentiary privilege under North Carolina law.
48 (3) Adversely affects the privacy or other rights of any person.
49 (c) A controller or processor is not in violation of this Chapter if:
50 (1) The controller or processor discloses personal data to a third-party controller
51 or processor in compliance with this Chapter.
Page 10 DRS35438-LRa-166

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The third party processes the personal data in violation of this Chapter.
2 (3) The disclosing controller or processor did not have actual knowledge of the
3 third party's intent to commit a violation of this Chapter.
4 (d) If a controller processes personal data under an exemption described in subsection (a)
5 of this section, the controller bears the burden of demonstrating that the processing qualifies for
6 the exemption.
7 (e) Nothing in this Chapter requires a controller, processor, third party, or consumer to
8 disclose a trade secret.
9 "§ 75F-11. No private cause of action.
10 A violation of this Chapter does not provide a basis for, nor is a violation of this Chapter
11 subject to, a private right of action under this Chapter or any other law.
12 "§ 75F-12. Enforcement.
13 (a) The Division shall establish and administer a system to receive consumer complaints
14 regarding a controller's or processor's alleged violation of this Chapter.
15 (b) The Division may investigate a consumer complaint to determine whether the
16 controller or processor violated or is violating this Chapter.
17 "§ 75F-13. Enforcement powers of the Attorney General.
18 (a) The Attorney General has the exclusive authority to enforce this Chapter. Upon
19 referral from the Division, the Attorney General may initiate an enforcement action against a
20 controller or processor for a violation of this Chapter.
21 (b) At least 45 days before the day on which the Attorney General initiates an
22 enforcement action against a controller or processor, the Attorney General shall provide the
23 controller or processor with the following:
24 (1) Written notice identifying each provision of this Chapter the Attorney General
25 alleges the controller or processor has violated or is violating.
26 (2) An explanation of the basis for each allegation.
27 (c) The Attorney General may not initiate an action if the controller or processor:
28 (1) Cures the noticed violation within 45 days after the day on which the
29 controller or processor receives the written notice described in subsection (b)
30 of this section.
31 (2) Provides the Attorney General an express written statement that the violation
32 has been cured and no further violation of the cured violation will occur.
33 (d) The Attorney General may initiate an action against a controller or processor who (i)
34 fails to cure a violation after receiving the notice described in subsection (b) of this section or (ii)
35 after curing a noticed violation and providing a written statement in accordance with subsection
36 (b) of this section, continues to violate this Chapter.
37 (e) In an action described in subsection (d) of this section, the Attorney General may
38 recover actual damages to the consumer; and for each violation described in subsection (d) of
39 this section, an amount not to exceed seven thousand five hundred dollars ($7,500).
40 (f) All money received from an action under this Chapter shall be deposited into the
41 Consumer Privacy Account established in G.S. 75F-14.
42 (g) If more than one controller or processor are involved in the same processing in
43 violation of this Chapter, the liability for the violation shall be allocated among the controllers or
44 processors in proportion to the comparative fault of each controller or processor.
45 "§ 75F-14. Consumer Privacy Account.
46 (a) There is created a restricted account known as the "Consumer Privacy Account." The
47 account shall be funded by money received through civil enforcement actions under this Chapter.
48 (b) Upon appropriation by the General Assembly, the account funds may be used by the
49 Attorney General for these purposes:
50 (1) Investigation and administrative costs incurred by the Division in
51 investigating consumer complaints alleging violations of this Chapter.
DRS35438-LRa-166 Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Recovery of costs and attorneys' fees accrued by the Attorney General in
2 enforcing this Chapter.
3 (3) Providing consumer and business education regarding consumer rights under
4 this Chapter and compliance with the provisions of this Chapter for controllers
5 and processors.
6 (c) If the balance in the account exceeds four million dollars ($4,000,000) at the close of
7 any fiscal year, the State Budget Director shall transfer the amount that exceeds four million
8 dollars ($4,000,000) into the General Fund.
9 "§ 75F-15. Attorney General report.
10 (a) The Attorney General and the Division shall compile a report evaluating the liability
11 and enforcement provisions of this Chapter, including the effectiveness of the Attorney General's
12 and the Division's efforts to enforce this Chapter and summarizing the data protected and not
13 protected by this Chapter, including, with reasonable detail, a list of the types of information that
14 are publicly available from State, local, and federal government sources.
15 (b) The Attorney General and the Division may update the report as new information
16 becomes available.
17 (c) The Attorney General and the Division shall submit the report to the Joint Legislative
18 Oversight Commission on Governmental Operations by July 1, 2028."
19 SECTION 3. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
20 Justice the sum of one million dollars ($1,000,000) in the 2026-2027 fiscal year for the purposes,
21 administration, and enforcement of this act.
22 SECTION 4. Sections 1 and 2 of this act become effective January 1, 2027. Section
23 3 of this act becomes effective July 1, 2026. The remainder of this act is effective when it
24 becomes law.
